WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:11.440
Moving from the flight to the landing — for landing it's important that beforehand

2
00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:15.440
we've already worked out which direction we'll fly the landing circuit, right or left,

3
00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:21.240
and above all it's important that everybody follows the same rules.

4
00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:25.720
Because in the landing phase we're not far from the ground, which means we have

5
00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:28.220
little or no time left to react.

6
00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:33.420
Up at 1,000 metres above the ground, when something goes wrong, you can take your time

7
00:00:33.420 --> 00:00:37.060
looking at the terrain and reacting. But near the landing site everything happens

8
00:00:37.060 --> 00:00:39.420
much faster, simply because the ground is right there.

9
00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:45.340
So the basic principle has to be that we all fly the same landing circuit, and that way

10
00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:50.920
we can guarantee that we can see what the others ahead of us are doing.

11
00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:55.640
The landing circuit works like this — we decide on a left-hand or right-hand circuit

12
00:00:55.640 --> 00:01:01.640
and then we head to the positioning leg and into the descending circle,

13
00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:06.240
which is where we lose height before entering a proper landing circuit.

14
00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:11.000
And in that descending circle it's important to fly three correct, full circles.

15
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.120
If it's a right circuit, you fly right circles; if it's a left circuit, you fly left circles.

16
00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:19.120
Then we end up at a sensible height for the landing circuit.

17
00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:23.520
We teach that height during your training. After one, two, three landings

18
00:01:53.940 --> 00:01:57.340
you can roughly hit the upwind leg. It varies, depending on the air mass,

19
00:01:57.340 --> 00:01:59.820
on where you are — it doesn't have to be the same every time.

20
00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:02.540
It can be completely different once wind is involved.

21
00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:06.260
That's why it's important to develop a feel for it, and to trust that feel.

22
00:02:06.260 --> 00:02:09.780
It takes everyone two, three, four flights before they get a handle on it,

23
00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:13.580
and that's exactly why your instructor is with you on the radio.

24
00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:17.500
I'm letting you know that very quickly you'll get the hang of it,

25
00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:20.500
and after a couple of guided flights you can do it independently.

26
00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:26.510
Upwind leg, crosswind leg, downwind — sorry, final leg.

27
00:02:26.510 --> 00:02:30.910
When we notice we're on the upwind leg, we need clearly enough height.

28
00:02:30.910 --> 00:02:34.230
Then we can comfortably turn into the crosswind leg,

29
00:02:34.230 --> 00:02:37.590
and we can also extend the crosswind leg

30
00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:41.750
if we have the room — fly out wider and round the corner.

31
00:02:41.750 --> 00:02:44.270
If we're too short, we won't notice it quite as much,

32
00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:48.230
and I can shorten it very simply, as shown here.

33
00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:54.280
Or we can fly the crosswind leg with S-turns,

34
00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:57.200
always following the correct reference points.

35
00:02:57.200 --> 00:03:00.920
And the great thing about those S-turns is that at any moment

36
00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:06.160
we can leave the crosswind leg and head into the final whenever it suits us.

37
00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:09.320
On final, just fly straight.

38
00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:12.760
We can make small course corrections ourselves

39
00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:16.120
if there's a bit of sidewind, but ultimately the important thing

40
00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:22.180
is to fly the target accurately.

41
00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:25.100
If we notice we're far too high,

42
00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:27.100
there are several options.

43
00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:30.020
We can, for example, make ourselves big.

44
00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:34.420
That means the pilot and the wing create relatively a lot of drag,

45
00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:36.980
and when we sit back in the harness,

46
00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:39.500
we glide well and have little drag.

47
00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:43.140
Or we make ourselves bigger by sitting up out of the harness,

48
00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:46.340
make sure the landing gear — your legs — is ready,

49
00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:47.940
and then we generate a lot of drag,

50
00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:49.380
which means we have a worse glide.

51
00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:52.220
Put differently, we can lose height efficiently.

52
00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:55.420
And that's how we get to our landing point.

53
00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:58.860
The other option is, very gently, S-turns.

54
00:03:58.860 --> 00:04:02.260
Those are allowed, too. Or, if we get there later,

55
00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:04.380
with little-ears.

56
00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:07.540
We pull little-ears in — simply put, the wing becomes smaller,

57
00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:11.420
we sink faster, and that also gives us a better chance

58
00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:13.100
of landing on the spot.

59
00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:16.020
The briefing for us is that in a 30-metre circle,

60
00:04:16.020 --> 00:04:18.300
if we touch down inside that circle,

61
00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:23.020
we've nailed a great landing.

62
00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:26.260
Important: if we have to pull little-ears,

63
00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:27.380
be aware that

64
00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:31.060
in that configuration we can't steer the wing very much.

65
00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:32.660
I can steer with weight-shift,

66
00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:35.540
but my freedom of movement is restricted,

67
00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:36.820
and we need to bear that in mind.

68
00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:39.060
So it's better to have the little-ears in already,

69
00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:44.620
rather than doing something unconsidered or in a panic,

70
00:04:44.620 --> 00:04:48.820
which usually doesn't go well.

71
00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:50.740
Then there are still situations

72
00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:53.420
where the landing turns out a bit differently than we'd planned,

73
00:04:53.420 --> 00:04:54.900
than we'd had in mind.

74
00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:58.060
For example, we've flown a landing circuit.

75
00:04:58.060 --> 00:04:59.700
We had a headwind originally,

76
00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:03.140
which is always nice — that lets us land into wind,

77
00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:04.780
the way we normally do.

78
00:05:04.780 --> 00:05:07.460
Now we suddenly have a tailwind,

79
00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:09.220
because the wind has shifted.

80
00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:10.740
That's not a drama.

81
00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:13.620
What's important is that we follow through with the landing circuit

82
00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:15.700
once we've committed to it,

83
00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:18.460
and we just deal with landing in the tailwind.

84
00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:22.100
With a tailwind we have more groundspeed in the final.

85
00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:25.540
That means we have to apply the brakes faster,

86
00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:27.540
more effectively,

87
00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:30.180
than we're used to on a normal landing.

88
00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:32.500
On a normal landing we go to

89
00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:36.020
the brakes slowly until we're just gliding above the ground.

90
00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:38.500
Landing in tailwind we need to flare crisply

91
00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:41.060
and decisively brake,

92
00:05:41.060 --> 00:05:42.780
to build up the momentum

93
00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:47.020
where the wing stops above us and right then both feet hit the ground.

94
00:05:47.020 --> 00:05:52.240
Even in tailwind you can make a clean, soft landing.

95
00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:56.280
A tailwind landing is no drama, it's just a skill

96
00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:57.520
you can practise.

97
00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:00.760
I'm not talking about 30 km/h tailwind, of course,

98
00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:03.680
but 5 to 10 km/h,

99
00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:05.960
which is something you can manage.

100
00:06:05.960 --> 00:06:08.760
It can also happen that we have to do an out-landing.

101
00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:11.480
The reason might be that the landing site is closed,

102
00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:13.080
and we have no other option.

103
00:06:13.080 --> 00:06:15.760
For an out-landing, it's important not to,

104
00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:19.240
if there's a slope, not to fly into the slope.

105
00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:23.880
If we're on a slope we don't fly directly into the hillside on flare,

106
00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:27.760
but we land parallel to the slope.

107
00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:30.360
There we make exactly the same kind of landing,

108
00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:32.280
touching down parallel to the slope.

109
00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:34.500
Good — done and dusted.

110
00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:38.300
Now it can also happen that we've misjudged things

111
00:06:38.300 --> 00:06:40.820
and we've overshot the landing site,

112
00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:45.260
and we end up at a car park where cars are parked.

113
00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:17.230
Whatever it is, there's a difference

114
00:07:17.230 --> 00:07:19.230
between flying onto it at 30 km/h

115
00:07:19.230 --> 00:07:21.230
and landing at only 5 km/h, or even 0,

116
00:07:21.230 --> 00:07:23.230
and that way we can still land on it.

117
00:07:23.230 --> 00:07:24.750
So to avoid a collision,

118
00:07:24.750 --> 00:07:29.230
the idea is to bleed off energy and not just stay up there and shout,

119
00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:30.230
and do nothing.

120
00:07:30.230 --> 00:07:32.390
Then we shouldn't worry about people watching us,

121
00:07:32.390 --> 00:07:35.420
or care about being in an embarrassing situation.

122
00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:38.700
It can happen. We've done something wrong,

123
00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:44.420
we can't reach the landing site anymore, and we end up landing on the way to it.

124
00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:47.540
Then there's the tree-landing chapter,

125
00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:50.580
but I've already chosen something better,

126
00:07:50.580 --> 00:07:53.580
because a tree landing is even worse.

127
00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:58.100
If you can choose, prefer the alternative to a tree,

128
00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:01.940
since then I'd have a better chance,

129
00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:07.940
of getting away with bumps and the like. The important thing in flight

130
00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:10.940
is to bleed off energy, via the brakes,

131
00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:15.500
and to protect the head — keep your head away from the branches.

132
00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:20.780
Important: there's good documentation about tree rescues.

133
00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:23.940
The same pilot is usually very safe in flight,

134
00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:25.820
with a lot of lines and fabric around them.

135
00:08:25.820 --> 00:08:29.580
The same is true for a reserve descent over a forest —

136
00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:31.980
there's a lot of fabric, a lot of line.

137
00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:36.820
It catches in the branches; very rarely or never does it happen

138
00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:39.620
that the pilot falls through the trees to the ground.

139
00:08:39.620 --> 00:08:43.620
Usually they stay hanging up there, and that's fundamentally safe.

140
00:08:43.620 --> 00:08:47.060
Most accidents that happen in this situation

141
00:08:47.060 --> 00:08:49.060
come from people going into shock.

142
00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:51.860
When they're in shock, clearly an emergency situation,

143
00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:55.620
they try to free themselves and end up falling.

144
00:08:55.620 --> 00:08:59.460
Because for example you might be hanging in a tree on a steep slope

145
00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:01.700
and the slope to the side is right there,

146
00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:03.380
and it looks like only two metres,

147
00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:05.900
but people don't notice that on the tree side

148
00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:07.420
they might be 15 metres up.

149
00:09:07.420 --> 00:09:10.140
And if you unclip from the harness and fall,

150
00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:12.700
15 metres is absolutely devastating.

151
00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:15.100
So important: if this happens,

152
00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:17.740
fundamentally, stay calm first.

153
00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:21.860
Calm, calm, calm, and then take your time and say,

154
00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:24.260
right, analyse the situation.

155
00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:27.900
The smartest move, if you're in fairly civilised terrain,

156
00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:30.780
is to inform the emergency services anyway.

157
00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.100
REGA, the Swiss air rescue, can be reached almost anywhere

158
00:09:34.100 --> 00:09:35.700
and they're glad to hear from you.

159
00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:37.700
They're glad to know

160
00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:40.700
where you are, whether you're OK,

161
00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:42.340
and whether you need help.

162
00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:44.580
In my view, you need help

163
00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:46.860
any time you notice that

164
00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:49.100
you're stuck in a tree,

165
00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:52.640
and higher than one or two metres.

166
00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:53.800
Call REGA,

167
00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:56.440
and getting yourself and the wing recovered with their help

168
00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:58.390
is much easier.

169
00:09:58.390 --> 00:10:00.390
Rather than risking a fall —

170
00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:03.030
as we said,

171
00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:04.830
falling from height.

172
00:10:04.830 --> 00:10:08.310
So basically — let people know what's going on,

173
00:10:08.310 --> 00:10:10.750
and then wait for help.

174
00:10:10.750 --> 00:10:12.230
It takes patience.

175
00:10:12.230 --> 00:10:15.870
In our region we're very lucky.

176
00:10:15.870 --> 00:10:17.870
A few times with REGA,

177
00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:19.750
they're very quick,

178
00:10:19.750 --> 00:10:21.710
and so we can say

179
00:10:21.710 --> 00:10:24.070
the rescue is set in motion very quickly.

180
00:10:24.070 --> 00:10:25.670
Another landing situation,

181
00:10:25.670 --> 00:10:27.310
which hopefully you never encounter,

182
00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:29.310
and that's why it's flagged,

183
00:10:29.310 --> 00:10:31.310
is a water landing.

184
00:10:31.310 --> 00:10:33.310
Water landings have to be avoided,

185
00:10:33.310 --> 00:10:35.310
because still water in winter

186
00:10:35.310 --> 00:10:37.310
can be very, very cold,

187
00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:41.310
and with your hands you can quickly get cold and stiff,

188
00:10:41.310 --> 00:10:43.310
and become unable

189
00:10:43.310 --> 00:10:45.310
to swim.

190
00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:47.310
Even worse is in a river.

191
00:10:47.310 --> 00:10:49.310
A river current is a trap.

192
00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:51.310
It's pretty uncontrollable,

193
00:10:51.310 --> 00:10:52.310
I'd say,

194
00:10:52.310 --> 00:10:54.310
it can be that...

195
00:10:54.310 --> 00:10:56.310
If at all possible,

196
00:10:56.310 --> 00:10:57.310
if I see

197
00:10:57.310 --> 00:10:58.310
I'm going to end up in water,

198
00:10:58.310 --> 00:11:00.310
open the harness early,

199
00:11:00.310 --> 00:11:02.310
so that when you actually touch the water,

200
00:11:02.310 --> 00:11:05.310
you can immediately swim away from the gear.

201
00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:07.310
But it's important,

202
00:11:07.310 --> 00:11:09.310
never before touching the water,

203
00:11:09.310 --> 00:11:10.310
to step out of the harness,

204
00:11:10.310 --> 00:11:12.310
because in the shock of the moment,

205
00:11:12.310 --> 00:11:13.310
with all the gear,

206
00:11:13.310 --> 00:11:14.310
if they're...

207
00:11:14.310 --> 00:11:15.310
we don't have it under control,

208
00:11:15.310 --> 00:11:16.310
and now we're five metres

209
00:11:16.310 --> 00:11:18.310
above the water and we jump,

210
00:11:18.310 --> 00:11:19.310
or we're at 20 metres,

211
00:11:19.310 --> 00:11:23.310
and that can also have very serious consequences

212
00:11:23.310 --> 00:11:25.310
if you misjudge it.

213
00:11:26.310 --> 00:11:29.310
(unclear)

214
00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:30.310
(unclear)

215
00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:32.310
You have to try

216
00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:33.310
to make it here,

217
00:11:33.310 --> 00:11:36.310
whether the intermediate stages get taken care of.

218
00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:38.310
You don't have much time

219
00:11:38.310 --> 00:11:39.310
to do it,

220
00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:40.310
and then you grab on.

221
00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:42.310
It's already there,

222
00:11:42.310 --> 00:11:44.310
I have to think now,

223
00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:45.310
it's up to you,

224
00:11:45.310 --> 00:11:47.310
have a look for yourself,

225
00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:48.310
even when I do,

226
00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:50.310
what I'm at now in the other river,

227
00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:51.310
you have to push again,

228
00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:52.310
yes,

229
00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:55.040
have a look there.

230
00:11:55.040 --> 00:12:01.440
If the whole landing business doesn't quite go to plan,

231
00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:09.280
or if someone has a landing that doesn't go quite as nicely as the K-shaped final flare

232
00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:15.480
and they get injured, it's also important that we know how to look after an injured pilot.

233
00:12:15.480 --> 00:12:21.800
With paragliding we unfortunately have one disadvantage: we're in a sitting position,

234
00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:26.600
meaning that if we come down hard, we're sitting,

235
00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:29.280
and it goes pretty directly into the spine.

236
00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:33.680
That's why spinal injuries in paragliding are not uncommon.

237
00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:38.920
And when we reach the injured pilot, it's really important to know that.

238
00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:46.360
It means we have to calm them down first, and then we'll fairly quickly notice how badly

239
00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:48.320
or where the pilot is hurt.

240
00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:53.080
If it's the back and breathing still works fine,

241
00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:57.960
the best thing is to leave them lying down and immediately inform REGA

242
00:12:57.960 --> 00:13:01.520
so they can come in with the helicopter and pick them up.

243
00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:06.120
When the helicopter comes, it's important to know it kicks up a lot of wind.

244
00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:10.280
As soon as it lands — meaning, get everything packed up, maybe your harness,

245
00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.160
maybe your wing, all the loose gear,

246
00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:18.680
stash it under a stone or something so nothing flies off into the rotors and endangers the helicopter.

247
00:13:18.680 --> 00:13:27.270
When the injury is to the back, it's important

248
00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:32.510
that if the pilot wants to sit up or drink something — that's a normal reaction,

249
00:13:32.510 --> 00:13:35.270
after an accident — we have to prevent that.

250
00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:39.030
We have to stay still, not move, as long as they're responsive.

251
00:13:39.030 --> 00:13:42.950
And also nothing to drink — that's also important,

252
00:13:42.950 --> 00:13:48.600
because we don't know if they have internal injuries or not.

253
00:13:48.600 --> 00:13:54.460
Now, now we move on to the topic of flight technique. The point is

254
00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:58.460
that we should know what our wing can actually do,

255
00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:00.660
or it's important what we can influence

256
00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:05.060
to make the wing glide better or sink less.

257
00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:08.660
And here it's quite simple — you can see it on this scale —

258
00:14:08.660 --> 00:14:12.060
that with a school wing,

259
00:14:13.060 --> 00:14:20.060
we get our best glide — meaning we travel from point A to point B with the most efficiency —

260
00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:26.060
when we have about 5 to 15 cm of brake contact.

261
00:14:26.060 --> 00:14:32.060
At that speed, we stay in the air as long as possible.

262
00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:35.060
That's the minimum sink in the scale.

263
00:14:35.060 --> 00:14:37.060
We don't travel the furthest,

264
00:14:37.060 --> 00:14:40.060
but per unit of time we stay aloft longest.

265
00:14:41.060 --> 00:14:43.060
Pulling a bit more brake, around 15-20 cm,

266
00:14:43.060 --> 00:14:45.060
we're a bit above trim speed.

267
00:14:45.060 --> 00:14:48.060
And as we approach minimum airspeed —

268
00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:51.060
the slowest the paraglider will still fly,

269
00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:53.060
before it really stalls,

270
00:14:53.060 --> 00:14:55.060
which we'll come to later —

271
00:14:55.060 --> 00:14:57.060
minimum airspeed is always with relatively strong brake input.

272
00:14:57.060 --> 00:14:59.060
We can really pull the brakes down,

273
00:14:59.060 --> 00:15:02.060
but important: keep your elbows pointing nicely forward.

274
00:15:02.060 --> 00:15:07.160
And then we're at about 40 cm,

275
00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:09.160
where we're already flying pretty slowly.

276
00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:11.160
The opposite we can also do,

277
00:15:11.160 --> 00:15:12.160
namely accelerate,

278
00:15:12.160 --> 00:15:14.160
when we use the speedbar,

279
00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:16.160
or in most cases,

280
00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:18.160
we can push it through,

281
00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:20.160
and then we pick up a lot of speed,

282
00:15:20.160 --> 00:15:21.160
because we're doing nothing other

283
00:15:21.160 --> 00:15:23.160
than reducing our angle of attack,

284
00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:25.160
so we go faster,

285
00:15:25.160 --> 00:15:28.160
and so the wing inherently flies faster.

286
00:15:28.160 --> 00:15:32.950
The accelerator, very simply put,

287
00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:35.950
we always use whenever we have a headwind.

288
00:15:35.950 --> 00:15:37.950
So fundamentally,

289
00:15:37.950 --> 00:16:08.620
we then play the brakes back and forth — (long stutter, omitted)

290
00:16:08.620 --> 00:16:10.620
the wings ahead on the landing site,

291
00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:13.620
or wherever we can still reach another landing spot.

292
00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:22.690
Then there's not only flying itself with take-off and landing.

293
00:16:22.690 --> 00:16:25.690
We've talked about it already, but it should be fun too.

294
00:16:25.690 --> 00:16:27.690
There's also so-called soaring.

295
00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:30.690
When you can use ridge lift,

296
00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:32.690
we call that soaring.

297
00:16:32.690 --> 00:16:35.690
When the broader wind

298
00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:36.690
flows up the slope,

299
00:16:36.690 --> 00:16:38.690
there's a band of lift.

300
00:16:38.690 --> 00:16:40.690
And in that lift band you can climb

301
00:16:40.690 --> 00:16:41.690
to higher altitudes.

302
00:16:41.690 --> 00:16:43.690
And it's not that hard.

303
00:16:43.690 --> 00:16:46.690
It's mostly wind-driven.

304
00:16:46.690 --> 00:16:48.690
There are also thermals,

305
00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:50.690
but you don't want to confuse it with thermals.

306
00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:52.690
Let's stick to soaring for now.

307
00:16:52.690 --> 00:16:53.690
There it's important,

308
00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:55.690
as a beginner, to keep distance from the slope,

309
00:16:55.690 --> 00:16:56.690
distance from the slope,

310
00:16:56.690 --> 00:16:58.690
and once again, distance from the slope.

311
00:16:58.690 --> 00:16:59.690
Why?

312
00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:02.690
Because we're constantly gliding.

313
00:17:02.690 --> 00:17:04.690
There might be other airspace users,

314
00:17:04.690 --> 00:17:06.690
who also fly in that area

315
00:17:06.690 --> 00:17:08.690
and create wake turbulence

316
00:17:08.690 --> 00:17:10.690
with their aircraft.

317
00:17:10.690 --> 00:17:12.690
And if you get drawn into one

318
00:17:12.690 --> 00:17:14.690
of those things quickly,

319
00:17:14.690 --> 00:17:17.690
or there can simply be more wind,

320
00:17:17.690 --> 00:17:19.690
and you get pushed more towards the slope,

321
00:17:19.690 --> 00:17:21.690
you have to be able to react

322
00:17:21.690 --> 00:17:23.690
to fly away from the slope again.

323
00:17:23.690 --> 00:17:27.690
And in general, always turn away from the slope.

324
00:17:27.690 --> 00:17:29.690
Not towards it,

325
00:17:29.690 --> 00:17:32.690
because then we have a tailwind component on the slope.

326
00:17:32.690 --> 00:17:34.690
The sink rate of the turn itself

327
00:17:34.690 --> 00:17:36.690
is hard to estimate.

328
00:17:36.690 --> 00:17:38.690
And if you head into the slope with a tailwind component,

329
00:17:38.690 --> 00:17:40.690
that's not good.

330
00:17:40.690 --> 00:17:42.690
So the things to bear in mind for soaring,

331
00:17:42.690 --> 00:17:45.690
always pay very close attention to them.

332
00:17:45.690 --> 00:17:46.690
Now we have,

333
00:17:46.690 --> 00:17:48.690
depending on the area,

334
00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:50.690
naturally thermal flying.

335
00:17:50.690 --> 00:17:52.690
And thermal flying

336
00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:53.690
is probably

337
00:17:53.690 --> 00:17:55.690
the supreme discipline

338
00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:56.690
of paragliding.

339
00:17:56.690 --> 00:17:59.690
We want to fly as far as possible.

340
00:17:59.690 --> 00:18:01.690
That means we use thermals

341
00:18:01.690 --> 00:18:03.690
as a means of transport.

342
00:18:03.690 --> 00:18:05.690
Because if you just glide,

343
00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:07.690
we only have our glide performance.

344
00:18:07.690 --> 00:18:09.690
If we launch from say 1,000 metres,

345
00:18:09.690 --> 00:18:13.690
we can glide about 8 kilometres.

346
00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:15.690
But now we have thermals.

347
00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:16.690
That means

348
00:18:16.690 --> 00:18:18.690
I have to know

349
00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:20.690
how to read those thermals

350
00:18:20.690 --> 00:18:22.690
and how I can fly them —

351
00:18:22.690 --> 00:18:24.690
thermal flying.

352
00:18:24.690 --> 00:18:26.690
To fly thermals,

353
00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:28.690
I need to know a few basic rules.

354
00:18:28.690 --> 00:18:30.690
The easiest, of course,

355
00:18:30.690 --> 00:18:32.690
is when we have visual feedback from the clouds —

356
00:18:32.690 --> 00:18:34.690
we see the thermal optically.

357
00:18:34.690 --> 00:18:36.690
Then we simply fly in that direction.

358
00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:38.690
Let's take an example with a cloud.

359
00:18:38.690 --> 00:18:40.690
If there's no wind,

360
00:18:40.690 --> 00:18:41.690
it's relatively easy

361
00:18:41.690 --> 00:18:42.690
to find the core.

362
00:18:42.690 --> 00:18:44.690
Just fly straight at the cloud.

363
00:18:44.690 --> 00:18:46.690
And once we've found the core relatively quickly,

364
00:18:46.690 --> 00:18:47.690
hopefully we climb.

365
00:18:47.690 --> 00:18:49.690
The whole thing gets harder when there's wind.

366
00:18:49.690 --> 00:18:51.690
Let's take an example here:

367
00:18:51.690 --> 00:18:53.690
the wind is coming from the left.

368
00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:55.690
The clouds drift like this.

369
00:18:55.690 --> 00:18:56.690
That means

370
00:18:56.690 --> 00:18:58.690
with the wing I have to fly to the upwind side

371
00:18:58.690 --> 00:18:59.690
of the cloud,

372
00:18:59.690 --> 00:19:01.690
so that I climb up nicely in the core

373
00:19:01.690 --> 00:19:04.690
while drifting with the wind.

374
00:19:04.690 --> 00:19:08.690
And that's how you exploit a thermal optimally.

375
00:19:08.690 --> 00:19:12.690
All of this is relatively easy to look at in the flatlands.

376
00:19:12.690 --> 00:19:14.690
It gets harder

377
00:19:14.690 --> 00:19:16.690
when you're in proper mountains

378
00:19:16.690 --> 00:19:19.690
where there are steep rock faces,

379
00:19:19.690 --> 00:19:21.690
because the thermals are sharp,

380
00:19:21.690 --> 00:19:23.690
they release very quickly.

381
00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:24.690
That means

382
00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:25.690
it's not broad,

383
00:19:25.690 --> 00:19:26.690
but compact,

384
00:19:26.690 --> 00:19:28.690
and correspondingly more turbulent.

385
00:19:28.690 --> 00:19:29.690
That's good

386
00:19:29.690 --> 00:19:31.690
if you can climb very fast

387
00:19:31.690 --> 00:19:33.690
in very tight circles,

388
00:19:33.690 --> 00:19:35.690
but for beginners

389
00:19:35.690 --> 00:19:37.690
that quickly leads to overload.

390
00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:39.690
What's important in thermals

391
00:19:39.690 --> 00:19:41.690
is to sit nice and loose,

392
00:19:41.690 --> 00:19:43.690
to do a lot with weight-shift.

393
00:19:43.690 --> 00:19:45.690
On the one hand,

394
00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:47.690
to centre the thermal nicely,

395
00:19:47.690 --> 00:19:48.690
but also very importantly,

396
00:19:48.690 --> 00:19:50.690
when you steer with weight,

397
00:19:50.690 --> 00:19:51.690
many pilots

398
00:19:51.690 --> 00:19:52.690
do that way too little,

399
00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:54.690
and they rely too heavily on the brakes,

400
00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:57.620
and too little on weight-shift.

401
00:19:57.620 --> 00:19:59.620
Really important —

402
00:19:59.620 --> 00:20:01.620
when you're sure

403
00:20:01.620 --> 00:20:02.620
that the next point

404
00:20:02.620 --> 00:20:03.620
you'd planned for

405
00:20:03.620 --> 00:20:05.620
you'll definitely reach.

406
00:20:05.620 --> 00:20:06.620
There's nothing worse

407
00:20:06.620 --> 00:20:08.620
than ditching a thermal early

408
00:20:08.620 --> 00:20:10.620
and then not making it to the next mountain

409
00:20:10.620 --> 00:20:11.620
low down,

410
00:20:11.620 --> 00:20:13.620
where you expect the next thermal.

411
00:20:13.620 --> 00:20:14.620
It's really important

412
00:20:14.620 --> 00:20:15.620
to thermal it out,

413
00:20:15.620 --> 00:20:17.620
and that takes a lot of patience,

414
00:20:17.620 --> 00:20:19.620
to get the height

415
00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:21.620
to safely reach the next planned

416
00:20:21.620 --> 00:20:22.620
point,

417
00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:23.620
where you assume

418
00:20:23.620 --> 00:20:25.620
the next thermal

419
00:20:25.620 --> 00:20:26.620
will be

420
00:20:26.620 --> 00:20:28.620
and lift you up again.

421
00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:31.620
All of this takes extreme amounts of experience,

422
00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:33.620
and at the start, be happy

423
00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:34.620
if in the flatlands,

424
00:20:34.620 --> 00:20:35.620
you can centre a thermal,

425
00:20:35.620 --> 00:20:37.620
climb up nicely and calmly,

426
00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:38.620
enjoy that,

427
00:20:38.620 --> 00:20:41.620
and the success will come with experience.

428
00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:46.180
In thermal flying,

429
00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:47.180
we can also

430
00:20:47.180 --> 00:20:50.180
encounter situations

431
00:20:50.180 --> 00:20:52.180
you'd rather not be in,

432
00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:54.180
namely a wing behaviour

433
00:20:54.180 --> 00:20:56.180
we're not used to.

434
00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:58.180
There can be collapses,

435
00:20:58.180 --> 00:21:00.180
there can be frontal collapses,

436
00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:03.180
which we'll now take up under the topic of big-ears.

437
00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:05.180
Excuse me.

438
00:21:05.180 --> 00:21:06.180
Pulling big-ears

439
00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:08.180
is a flight manoeuvre.

440
00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:10.180
When you take the SHV's

441
00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:11.180
brevet exam,

442
00:21:11.180 --> 00:21:14.180
the brevet-relevant manoeuvres

443
00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:16.180
are

444
00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:17.180
the ones beautifully

445
00:21:17.180 --> 00:21:18.180
explained by video,

446
00:21:18.180 --> 00:21:19.180
because for the brevet,

447
00:21:19.180 --> 00:21:21.180
you have to be able to fly

448
00:21:21.180 --> 00:21:23.180
certain manoeuvres.

449
00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:25.180
We'll start with little-ears,

450
00:21:25.180 --> 00:21:26.180
which we've already heard about

451
00:21:26.180 --> 00:21:27.180
during the landing.

452
00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:29.180
Little-ears is nothing more than

453
00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:31.180
the outermost lines

454
00:21:31.180 --> 00:21:32.180
of each side —

455
00:21:32.180 --> 00:21:34.180
it's the outermost A-line,

456
00:21:34.180 --> 00:21:36.180
not to be confused with the stabilo line.

457
00:21:36.180 --> 00:21:38.180
The stabilo line is on the outside

458
00:21:38.180 --> 00:21:39.180
of the paraglider,

459
00:21:39.180 --> 00:21:40.180
usually colour-coded,

460
00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:42.180
separate and very thin.

461
00:21:42.180 --> 00:21:44.180
But it's the outermost A-line

462
00:21:44.180 --> 00:21:46.180
that we use to inflate the wing on launch.

463
00:21:46.180 --> 00:21:47.180
On some

464
00:21:47.180 --> 00:21:50.180
wing models it's separated, on some it's bundled together.

465
00:21:50.180 --> 00:21:52.180
And it's always the outermost A-line,

466
00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:54.180
left and right,

467
00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:56.180
and then we pull our little-ears.

468
00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:58.180
We collapse the tips and we can wonderfully

469
00:21:58.180 --> 00:22:00.180
practise — with weight-shift

470
00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:02.180
we can still steer the wing.

471
00:22:02.180 --> 00:22:04.180
Little-ears, as I said,

472
00:22:04.180 --> 00:22:06.180
for example when you have a high-altitude landing

473
00:22:06.180 --> 00:22:08.180
and need to come down a bit faster —

474
00:22:08.180 --> 00:22:09.180
great manoeuvre —

475
00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:11.180
or if you simply want more sink

476
00:22:11.180 --> 00:22:12.180
to generate,

477
00:22:12.180 --> 00:22:13.180
to get to know the wing,

478
00:22:13.180 --> 00:22:14.180
doing little-ears

479
00:22:14.180 --> 00:22:16.180
is absolutely a good manoeuvre,

480
00:22:16.180 --> 00:22:17.180
it really is.

481
00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:19.180
There are also big-ears.

482
00:22:19.180 --> 00:22:21.180
Then depending on the wing model,

483
00:22:21.180 --> 00:22:23.180
we take not just the outermost A-line,

484
00:22:23.180 --> 00:22:25.180
but the second outermost A-line as well,

485
00:22:25.180 --> 00:22:26.180
when you have one over there.

486
00:22:26.180 --> 00:22:29.180
And then we can fold in much more of the ears.

487
00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:31.180
Really important: there are also wings

488
00:22:31.180 --> 00:22:33.180
that have only two attachment points.

489
00:22:33.180 --> 00:22:35.180
And there you're not allowed to pull both in

490
00:22:35.180 --> 00:22:36.180
at the same time,

491
00:22:36.180 --> 00:22:37.180
or you get a frontal collapse.

492
00:22:37.180 --> 00:22:39.180
Otherwise we do nothing different

493
00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:41.180
from little-ears as I described,

494
00:22:41.180 --> 00:22:43.210
and for big-ears,

495
00:22:43.210 --> 00:22:45.210
we then take the hand from the inside

496
00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:46.210
and bend down,

497
00:22:46.210 --> 00:22:49.210
so we get about 15 or 20 more centimetres of line,

498
00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:51.210
and then we pull them in.

499
00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:52.210
For big-ears.

500
00:22:52.210 --> 00:22:54.210
Really important with big-ears,

501
00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:56.210
to simultaneously,

502
00:22:56.210 --> 00:22:58.210
as you're pulling the lines in,

503
00:22:58.210 --> 00:23:00.210
accelerate.

504
00:23:00.210 --> 00:23:01.210
Because only then

505
00:23:01.210 --> 00:23:02.210
can we prevent

506
00:23:02.210 --> 00:23:03.210
us from pulling in too much ear,

507
00:23:03.210 --> 00:23:04.210
too much drag,

508
00:23:04.210 --> 00:23:06.210
the wing flies slowly

509
00:23:06.210 --> 00:23:08.210
and then truly stalls.

510
00:23:08.210 --> 00:23:10.210
By accelerating,

511
00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:11.210
by pushing the bar, by pulling the lines,

512
00:23:11.210 --> 00:23:12.210
and now together,

513
00:23:12.210 --> 00:23:14.210
the wing is once again

514
00:23:14.210 --> 00:23:16.210
flying at a normal angle,

515
00:23:16.210 --> 00:23:18.210
despite the extra drag

516
00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:19.210
from the ears being pulled.

517
00:23:19.210 --> 00:23:21.240
Afterwards, to open the ears,

518
00:23:21.240 --> 00:23:23.240
just let go.

519
00:23:23.240 --> 00:23:26.240
Only when the ears are completely open

520
00:23:26.240 --> 00:23:28.240
do you come off the speedbar.

521
00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:29.370
Again here,

522
00:23:29.370 --> 00:23:31.370
if we pull the ears in,

523
00:23:31.370 --> 00:23:32.370
let go, come off the bar —

524
00:23:32.370 --> 00:23:33.370
if you come off the accelerator,

525
00:23:33.370 --> 00:23:35.370
we still have a lot of drag,

526
00:23:35.370 --> 00:23:37.370
and the wing flies slowly

527
00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:39.370
and by coming off the bar,

528
00:23:39.370 --> 00:23:40.370
it can be

529
00:23:40.370 --> 00:23:42.370
that we then go directly into a true stall,

530
00:23:42.370 --> 00:23:43.370
which can happen,

531
00:23:43.370 --> 00:23:44.370
and we want to prevent that.

532
00:23:44.370 --> 00:23:46.370
A stall is nothing other

533
00:23:46.370 --> 00:23:48.370
than that we fly too slowly.

534
00:23:48.370 --> 00:23:50.370
Our wing's flying speed,

535
00:23:50.370 --> 00:23:51.370
the forward airspeed,

536
00:23:51.370 --> 00:23:53.370
we've fallen below it.

537
00:23:53.370 --> 00:23:54.370
It tips,

538
00:23:54.370 --> 00:23:56.370
essentially backwards,

539
00:23:56.370 --> 00:23:58.370
and totally

540
00:23:58.370 --> 00:23:59.370
empties from the wing.

541
00:23:59.370 --> 00:24:00.370
There's a pre-stage,

542
00:24:00.370 --> 00:24:01.370
the parachutal stall,

543
00:24:01.370 --> 00:24:02.370
the wing is still inflated.

544
00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:04.370
We have no forward speed anymore,

545
00:24:04.370 --> 00:24:06.370
and we only have sink,

546
00:24:06.370 --> 00:24:08.370
and you sense it through the wing,

547
00:24:08.370 --> 00:24:10.370
that there's no forward speed,

548
00:24:10.370 --> 00:24:11.370
it feels strange.

549
00:24:11.370 --> 00:24:12.370
The wing is mushy,

550
00:24:12.370 --> 00:24:14.370
then we're flying slowly,

551
00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:16.370
and we've got the brakes there again.

552
00:24:16.370 --> 00:24:19.370
Or flying with a really wet wing,

553
00:24:19.370 --> 00:24:20.370
it can happen

554
00:24:20.370 --> 00:24:22.370
that we go into a parachutal stall.

555
00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:23.370
Then fundamentally it's important,

556
00:24:23.370 --> 00:24:24.370
we're flying slowly,

557
00:24:24.370 --> 00:24:25.370
what helps,

558
00:24:25.370 --> 00:24:27.370
is the move from slow to fast,

559
00:24:27.370 --> 00:24:28.370
we need to speed up.

560
00:24:28.370 --> 00:24:29.370
That means,

561
00:24:29.370 --> 00:24:31.370
immediately grab the A-risers

562
00:24:31.370 --> 00:24:33.370
and push,

563
00:24:33.370 --> 00:24:35.370
so that it picks up speed,

564
00:24:35.370 --> 00:24:36.370
or use the accelerator,

565
00:24:36.370 --> 00:24:37.370
as it were,

566
00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:38.370
the whole accelerator,

567
00:24:38.370 --> 00:24:39.370
we want to get back

568
00:24:39.370 --> 00:24:41.370
into normal position,

569
00:24:41.370 --> 00:24:43.370
so that we have speed on the wing

570
00:24:43.370 --> 00:24:45.370
and come out of the stall.

571
00:24:45.370 --> 00:24:48.270
What can also happen,

572
00:24:48.270 --> 00:24:49.270
in thermal flying,

573
00:24:49.270 --> 00:24:50.270
is that as we fly,

574
00:24:50.270 --> 00:24:52.270
we get hit by wind shear

575
00:24:52.270 --> 00:24:53.270
and the wing collapses

576
00:24:53.270 --> 00:24:55.270
up to 50%.

577
00:24:55.270 --> 00:24:57.400
Completely out of nowhere.

578
00:24:57.400 --> 00:24:59.400
You get a real shock at first.

579
00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:00.400
That's normal at the start,

580
00:25:00.400 --> 00:25:01.400
but here too

581
00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:02.400
it's important

582
00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:04.400
that we react, and react actively.

583
00:25:04.400 --> 00:25:05.400
If we do nothing,

584
00:25:05.400 --> 00:25:06.400
what happens is,

585
00:25:06.400 --> 00:25:07.400
after the collapse the wing

586
00:25:07.400 --> 00:25:08.400
will have extremely high drag.

587
00:25:08.400 --> 00:25:09.400
And it will turn to the side

588
00:25:09.400 --> 00:25:10.400
of the wing

589
00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:11.400
where the collapse happened.

590
00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:13.400
With a few hundred metres of altitude

591
00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:15.400
things can quickly turn bad.

592
00:25:15.400 --> 00:25:16.400
That's why it's important

593
00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:18.400
that we react quickly.

594
00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:19.400
Whether it's a collapse or a stall

595
00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:20.400
is the same.

596
00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:21.400
When a collapse happens,

597
00:25:21.400 --> 00:25:22.400
the basic principle has to be:

598
00:25:22.400 --> 00:25:24.400
weight-shift to the open side,

599
00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:26.400
lightly brake against the turn.

600
00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:28.400
Brake, if necessary,

601
00:25:28.400 --> 00:25:30.400
so that we can keep flying straight

602
00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:33.400
and then the basic principle is to stabilise

603
00:25:33.400 --> 00:25:35.400
and then react.

604
00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:37.400
Then we can deal with the collapse

605
00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:40.520
to reopen it.

606
00:25:40.520 --> 00:25:44.410
When we

607
00:25:44.410 --> 00:25:46.410
do descent manoeuvres,

608
00:25:46.410 --> 00:25:47.410
I mean,

609
00:25:47.410 --> 00:25:48.410
we have to come down quickly,

610
00:25:48.410 --> 00:25:50.410
because for example

611
00:25:50.410 --> 00:25:51.410
the weather is changing.

612
00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:52.410
We say,

613
00:25:52.410 --> 00:25:53.410
we don't want to be flying so long,

614
00:25:53.410 --> 00:25:54.410
the weather is moving in.

615
00:25:54.410 --> 00:25:55.410
It can also be

616
00:25:55.410 --> 00:25:57.410
that it makes sense

617
00:25:57.410 --> 00:25:59.410
to know certain descent manoeuvres.

618
00:25:59.410 --> 00:26:01.410
Big-ears,

619
00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:02.410
which we talked about already,

620
00:26:02.410 --> 00:26:03.410
that's very important

621
00:26:03.410 --> 00:26:05.410
and a good descent manoeuvre,

622
00:26:05.410 --> 00:26:07.410
as with big-ears,

623
00:26:07.410 --> 00:26:08.410
you can still steer with weight

624
00:26:08.410 --> 00:26:10.410
and fly forward.

625
00:26:10.410 --> 00:26:11.410
So that means,

626
00:26:11.410 --> 00:26:13.410
if we're in a strong band of lift,

627
00:26:13.410 --> 00:26:15.410
fly away from the lift band,

628
00:26:15.410 --> 00:26:17.410
and don't stay inside it.

629
00:26:17.410 --> 00:26:18.410
The B-stall,

630
00:26:18.410 --> 00:26:19.410
which is also described

631
00:26:19.410 --> 00:26:21.410
and which the brevet asks about,

632
00:26:21.410 --> 00:26:23.410
has a big disadvantage:

633
00:26:23.410 --> 00:26:24.410
that we do it here,

634
00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:26.410
and although we generate a lot of sink,

635
00:26:26.410 --> 00:26:27.410
we can't steer at all,

636
00:26:27.410 --> 00:26:28.410
but,

637
00:26:28.410 --> 00:26:29.410
I mean,

638
00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:30.410
if we're in a band of lift,

639
00:26:30.410 --> 00:26:31.410
in strong lift,

640
00:26:31.410 --> 00:26:32.410
we're still stuck inside.

641
00:26:32.410 --> 00:26:33.410
And as soon as we're out,

642
00:26:33.410 --> 00:26:34.410
we fly out.

643
00:26:34.410 --> 00:26:35.410
B-stall is nothing more

644
00:26:35.410 --> 00:26:36.410
than that we take,

645
00:26:36.410 --> 00:26:37.410
sit there,

646
00:26:37.410 --> 00:26:38.410
not the A-risers,

647
00:26:38.410 --> 00:26:40.410
but the B-risers,

648
00:26:40.410 --> 00:26:41.410
the B-risers,

649
00:26:41.410 --> 00:26:43.410
and slowly pull them down to us.

650
00:26:43.410 --> 00:26:44.410
Important is

651
00:26:44.410 --> 00:26:45.410
that we have the brakes,

652
00:26:45.410 --> 00:26:46.410
totally normally in hand,

653
00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:47.410
not actually wrapped,

654
00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:49.410
we just pull them down at the same time.

655
00:26:49.410 --> 00:26:50.410
Otherwise it's...

656
00:26:50.410 --> 00:26:51.410
B-risers,

657
00:26:51.410 --> 00:26:52.410
the B-risers,

658
00:26:52.410 --> 00:26:53.410
the B-risers,

659
00:26:53.410 --> 00:26:54.410
the B-risers,

660
00:26:54.410 --> 00:26:55.410
the B-risers,

661
00:26:55.410 --> 00:26:56.410
to pull down.

662
00:26:56.410 --> 00:26:57.410
And then there's a fold in the lower sail,

663
00:26:57.410 --> 00:26:59.410
and noticeably, then only sink.

664
00:26:59.410 --> 00:27:01.410
And you can sit comfortably in the harness,

665
00:27:01.410 --> 00:27:02.410
hold it,

666
00:27:02.410 --> 00:27:03.410
with me in training,

667
00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:06.410
or under guidance from a flight instructor on the radio.

668
00:27:06.410 --> 00:27:08.410
We've practised that well.

669
00:27:08.410 --> 00:27:09.410
Afterwards,

670
00:27:09.410 --> 00:27:10.410
to release the B-stall,

671
00:27:10.410 --> 00:27:11.410
it's nothing more

672
00:27:11.410 --> 00:27:13.410
than at first

673
00:27:13.410 --> 00:27:14.410
slowly,

674
00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:15.410
and then completely,

675
00:27:15.410 --> 00:27:16.410
on the four,

676
00:27:16.410 --> 00:27:17.410
and also on the four,

677
00:27:17.410 --> 00:27:18.410
and on the four,

678
00:27:18.410 --> 00:27:19.410
and on the four.

679
00:28:13.830 --> 00:28:15.830
And then there's 4,000 kilos.

680
00:28:15.830 --> 00:28:17.830
And not everyone handles that.

681
00:28:17.830 --> 00:28:18.830
And that's why it's important

682
00:28:18.830 --> 00:28:21.830
to do some really solid training,

683
00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:22.830
in a safe,

684
00:28:22.830 --> 00:28:24.830
guided SIV course,

685
00:28:24.830 --> 00:28:25.830
or there's also the option

686
00:28:25.830 --> 00:28:26.830
of the G-Force Trainer,

687
00:28:26.830 --> 00:28:27.830
which wonderfully,

688
00:28:27.830 --> 00:28:28.830
in a simulator,

689
00:28:28.830 --> 00:28:29.830
lets me

690
00:28:29.830 --> 00:28:30.830
get to know myself,

691
00:28:30.830 --> 00:28:31.830
how I react

692
00:28:31.830 --> 00:28:33.830
in a spiral dive.

693
00:28:33.830 --> 00:28:34.830
Stuff like that.

694
00:28:34.830 --> 00:28:36.980
The new manoeuvre,

695
00:28:36.980 --> 00:28:38.980
which the touring brevet now requires,

696
00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:40.980
but is still worth mentioning,

697
00:28:40.980 --> 00:28:41.980
is

698
00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:43.980
that you essentially do a spiral dive

699
00:28:43.980 --> 00:28:44.980
with a held collapse.

700
00:28:44.980 --> 00:28:45.980
That's the first one,

701
00:28:45.980 --> 00:28:47.980
as already discussed.

702
00:28:47.980 --> 00:28:48.980
And then you do

703
00:28:48.980 --> 00:28:49.980
on the opposite side,

704
00:28:49.980 --> 00:28:50.980
the so-called wing-spiral.

705
00:28:50.980 --> 00:28:52.980
It has an advantage:

706
00:28:52.980 --> 00:28:53.980
you generate a lot of sink,

707
00:28:53.980 --> 00:28:55.980
but have less G-load.

708
00:28:55.980 --> 00:28:56.980
We're back into the G-forces

709
00:28:56.980 --> 00:28:58.980
and how it presents itself.

710
00:28:58.980 --> 00:28:59.980
It's also a manoeuvre

711
00:28:59.980 --> 00:29:00.980
that belongs in an SIV,

712
00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:01.980
but important

713
00:29:01.980 --> 00:29:03.980
that you've heard of it.

714
00:29:03.980 --> 00:29:05.980
What might come up in the theory test

715
00:29:05.980 --> 00:29:06.980
is the spin,

716
00:29:06.980 --> 00:29:07.980
the twist,

717
00:29:07.980 --> 00:29:08.980
as well as wingovers.

718
00:29:08.980 --> 00:29:09.980
And you need to know

719
00:29:09.980 --> 00:29:10.980
what that is.

720
00:29:10.980 --> 00:29:12.980
Spin is nothing other

721
00:29:12.980 --> 00:29:14.980
than one side being

722
00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:15.980
pulled too far down.

723
00:29:15.980 --> 00:29:16.980
For example,

724
00:29:16.980 --> 00:29:17.980
as in a spiral exit,

725
00:29:17.980 --> 00:29:20.980
but done totally motor-skill style.

726
00:29:20.980 --> 00:29:22.980
And then the airspeed disappears

727
00:29:22.980 --> 00:29:24.980
and the wing rotates negatively.

728
00:29:24.980 --> 00:29:25.980
That's a spin.

729
00:29:28.420 --> 00:29:30.420
If you can do this very quickly,

730
00:29:30.420 --> 00:29:31.420
it can be

731
00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:32.420
that the wing rotates above,

732
00:29:32.420 --> 00:29:34.420
and we below,

733
00:29:34.420 --> 00:29:35.420
have the momentum,

734
00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:37.420
where the wing first follows with too little speed.

735
00:29:37.420 --> 00:29:39.420
I can ride this out of the wing's shoulder

736
00:29:39.420 --> 00:29:40.420
and find myself

737
00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:42.420
in this position from the start.

738
00:29:42.420 --> 00:29:44.420
And then I can imagine,

739
00:29:44.420 --> 00:29:45.420
these wire braids,

740
00:29:45.420 --> 00:29:47.420
happens really quickly,

741
00:29:47.420 --> 00:29:49.420
the wing makes a bit of a back-shoot.

742
00:29:49.420 --> 00:29:51.420
And now I have a twist.

743
00:29:51.420 --> 00:29:52.420
That means,

744
00:29:52.420 --> 00:29:53.420
nothing other than,

745
00:29:53.420 --> 00:29:54.420
the risers got twisted up.

746
00:29:54.420 --> 00:29:56.450
Then I'm in a twist.

747
00:29:56.450 --> 00:29:58.450
That's the term for it.

748
00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:01.670
When I...

749
00:30:01.670 --> 00:30:02.670
How do we fly wingovers?

750
00:30:02.670 --> 00:30:03.670
It's nothing other than

751
00:30:03.670 --> 00:30:06.670
getting the wing to roll.

752
00:30:06.670 --> 00:30:07.730
That means,

753
00:30:07.730 --> 00:30:08.730
I choose

754
00:30:08.730 --> 00:30:09.730
a free side,

755
00:30:09.730 --> 00:30:10.730
left or right,

756
00:30:10.730 --> 00:30:12.730
and apply weight and brake to that side.

757
00:30:12.730 --> 00:30:13.730
And as soon as I'm back

758
00:30:13.730 --> 00:30:14.730
below in the pendulum,

759
00:30:14.730 --> 00:30:16.730
I already release on the opposite side,

760
00:30:16.730 --> 00:30:18.730
the brake input.

761
00:30:18.730 --> 00:30:19.730
Crazy stuff!

762
00:30:19.730 --> 00:30:23.730
Where it looks Gold and Spezler-style

763
00:30:23.730 --> 00:30:26.730
and later also with brake-input timing.

764
00:30:26.730 --> 00:30:28.730
Just the brake-input dosing

765
00:30:28.730 --> 00:30:29.730
happens.

766
00:30:29.730 --> 00:30:33.730
Then the brake input comes onto the brake input.

767
00:30:33.730 --> 00:30:35.730
Then the brake input comes onto the brake input.

768
00:30:35.730 --> 00:30:36.730
Then come the certain brake inputs.

769
00:30:36.730 --> 00:30:40.790
Then come the

770
00:30:40.790 --> 00:30:41.730
people,

771
00:30:41.730 --> 00:30:42.730
the people, the people, the people, the people.

772
00:30:42.730 --> 00:30:44.730
Eye-stunts, you just notice,

773
00:30:44.730 --> 00:30:47.770
you have to get to know your wing and train.

774
00:30:47.770 --> 00:30:50.170
The same is nothing other than

775
00:30:50.170 --> 00:30:52.450
that we strongly brake the wing standing still.

776
00:30:52.450 --> 00:30:54.050
Wing goes behind.

777
00:30:54.050 --> 00:30:56.610
More than a person for us, and now we wait,

778
00:30:56.610 --> 00:30:58.610
until the wing once again hundreds.

779
00:30:58.610 --> 00:31:01.520
Before, wait until the lower stage.

780
00:31:01.520 --> 00:31:03.200
Now we want to brake again.

781
00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:05.720
There it is mostly very common danger, that people already

782
00:31:05.720 --> 00:31:08.000
while descending start braking again,

783
00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:09.160
and so the wing stops,

784
00:31:09.160 --> 00:31:11.200
but if we really wait in the lower stage,

785
00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:13.040
until we're a bit past the lowest point,

786
00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:14.240
and then we brake again.

787
00:31:14.240 --> 00:31:16.480
That's not a path we get for free.

788
00:31:16.480 --> 00:31:18.400
There they want to see in the brevet,

789
00:31:18.400 --> 00:31:22.930
that it pendulums up to the trailing and leading edge.

790
00:31:22.930 --> 00:31:25.570
It's not the craziest climb, but still,

791
00:31:25.570 --> 00:31:26.930
we have to work the wing,

792
00:31:26.930 --> 00:31:27.970
and that's a goal,

793
00:31:27.970 --> 00:31:30.650
so that we can get to know the whole thing.

794
00:31:31.370 --> 00:31:33.050
Now, the manoeuvres,

795
00:31:33.050 --> 00:31:36.050
like wingover and so on,

796
00:31:36.050 --> 00:31:38.290
it can all be a lot of fun

797
00:31:38.290 --> 00:31:40.170
and makes total sense

798
00:31:40.170 --> 00:31:41.170
to train.

799
00:31:41.170 --> 00:31:42.970
But it can also always happen

800
00:31:43.090 --> 00:31:45.770
that the whole thing goes pear-shaped.

801
00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:51.090
And the topic of the reserve parachute,

802
00:31:51.090 --> 00:31:53.570
the next chapter looks ahead,

803
00:31:54.940 --> 00:31:55.540
always and forever,

804
00:31:55.540 --> 00:31:56.380
you must know,

805
00:31:56.380 --> 00:31:59.820
your reserve parachute doesn't have anything to do (with luck).

806
00:32:01.530 --> 00:32:04.730
It's absolutely useless if you have a reserve

807
00:32:04.730 --> 00:32:06.450
and you don't pull it.

808
00:32:06.970 --> 00:32:09.090
And the very, very important principle —

809
00:32:09.490 --> 00:32:11.290
skydivers have a system

810
00:32:11.290 --> 00:32:12.570
where, when they have a certain time

811
00:32:12.570 --> 00:32:14.210
or a certain altitude they've passed,

812
00:32:14.330 --> 00:32:17.570
an automatic reserve is deployed.

813
00:32:17.570 --> 00:32:19.850
Most paragliders don't have that,

814
00:32:19.850 --> 00:32:21.330
and by design

815
00:32:21.330 --> 00:32:23.770
there's never been a really clean solution found.

816
00:32:23.770 --> 00:32:24.570
That means

817
00:32:24.570 --> 00:32:27.570
in an emergency situation, more than ever as a pilot,

818
00:32:27.570 --> 00:32:29.410
actively pull the reserve parachute.

819
00:32:29.410 --> 00:32:31.050
And only if you don't pull,

820
00:32:31.050 --> 00:32:33.130
it'll never work.

821
00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:36.080
We need to be very, very aware of that.

822
00:32:37.190 --> 00:32:38.790
When we have the situation,

823
00:32:38.790 --> 00:32:40.110
loss of control,

824
00:32:40.590 --> 00:32:41.670
and we do nothing,

825
00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:44.070
and the situation doesn't improve.

826
00:32:44.590 --> 00:32:46.310
First try to improve it,

827
00:32:46.310 --> 00:32:48.030
and if you say, OK this isn't working.

828
00:32:48.030 --> 00:32:49.430
Now I can't control it,

829
00:32:49.430 --> 00:32:51.630
now I have to my reserve

830
00:32:53.010 --> 00:32:54.330
grab and pull.

831
00:32:54.650 --> 00:32:56.050
When you pull the reserve,

832
00:32:56.050 --> 00:32:57.210
the basic principle

833
00:32:57.210 --> 00:32:59.610
is always: when it's uncontrollable.

834
00:32:59.810 --> 00:33:01.570
Meaning a state

835
00:33:01.570 --> 00:33:04.210
where I don't know which way is up or down,

836
00:33:04.210 --> 00:33:05.210
and a state

837
00:33:05.210 --> 00:33:07.010
you can't within a very short time,

838
00:33:07.010 --> 00:33:08.650
we say three seconds,

839
00:33:09.010 --> 00:33:11.730
two-to-three seconds, stabilise,

840
00:33:11.730 --> 00:33:13.130
and get back into normal flight,

841
00:33:13.130 --> 00:33:14.530
it's time for the reserve.

842
00:33:14.650 --> 00:33:16.850
I've got the whole thing at low altitude,

843
00:33:16.850 --> 00:33:18.530
meaning I'm in the descent,

844
00:33:18.530 --> 00:33:20.090
in the landing area,

845
00:33:20.090 --> 00:33:21.570
and yes, I'm low.

846
00:33:21.570 --> 00:33:22.650
And I have a problem.

847
00:33:22.650 --> 00:33:24.010
Immediately pull the reserve.

848
00:33:24.010 --> 00:33:25.210
Loss of control,

849
00:33:25.210 --> 00:33:26.890
I don't know what the wing is doing,

850
00:33:26.890 --> 00:33:29.330
immediately pull the reserve.

851
00:33:29.330 --> 00:33:33.210
That can happen out of a cravat, for example.

852
00:33:33.210 --> 00:33:35.170
It can happen that you have two collapses,

853
00:33:35.170 --> 00:33:37.570
if we planned a frill-based manoeuvre,

854
00:33:37.570 --> 00:33:40.610
something uncontrolled, immediately reserve.

855
00:33:40.610 --> 00:33:41.930
It can also be

856
00:33:41.930 --> 00:33:43.050
that there's a mid-air collision,

857
00:33:43.050 --> 00:33:44.050
because it's running again.

858
00:33:44.050 --> 00:33:46.330
We have relatively a lot of airspace,

859
00:33:46.330 --> 00:33:48.530
but other airspace users too,

860
00:33:48.530 --> 00:33:50.610
and if we have a mid-air,

861
00:33:50.610 --> 00:33:52.610
then it's safer right away

862
00:33:52.610 --> 00:33:55.250
to pull the reserve parachute.

863
00:33:55.250 --> 00:33:56.650
We know, even

864
00:33:56.650 --> 00:33:58.930
if we'd go from the mid-air and fly on,

865
00:33:58.930 --> 00:34:01.650
we know that the aircraft is so heavily damaged

866
00:34:01.650 --> 00:34:03.770
that perhaps exactly in the worst moment,

867
00:34:03.770 --> 00:34:05.090
say in the final approach,

868
00:34:05.090 --> 00:34:06.090
we can't,

869
00:34:06.090 --> 00:34:09.130
react and pull the reserve.

870
00:34:09.130 --> 00:34:10.370
So in a mid-air,

871
00:34:10.370 --> 00:34:12.010
if we still have flight

872
00:34:12.010 --> 00:34:14.330
over a large salt flat — pull the reserve,

873
00:34:14.330 --> 00:34:16.330
even if it seems controllable,

874
00:34:16.330 --> 00:34:18.330
the first basic principle applies again.

875
00:34:18.330 --> 00:34:22.570
There's no thinking about it — pull the reserve immediately.

876
00:34:22.570 --> 00:34:23.570
It can also be

877
00:34:23.570 --> 00:34:25.570
that there's a medical issue.

878
00:34:25.570 --> 00:34:26.570
Your flight is out,

879
00:34:26.570 --> 00:34:28.410
and your vision goes black.

880
00:34:28.410 --> 00:34:30.250
No matter what, it's not OK.

881
00:34:30.250 --> 00:34:33.010
Then the reserve is the best option,

882
00:34:33.010 --> 00:34:34.610
rather than somewhere uncontrolled,

883
00:34:34.610 --> 00:34:35.810
wandering into terrain,

884
00:34:35.810 --> 00:34:37.210
with the paraglider.

885
00:34:37.210 --> 00:34:39.210
Not a good option.

886
00:34:39.210 --> 00:34:41.770
What also nowadays very rarely

887
00:34:41.770 --> 00:34:43.770
happens, almost never anymore,

888
00:34:43.770 --> 00:34:44.770
is material failure,

889
00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:45.770
but it could happen,

890
00:34:45.770 --> 00:34:47.770
that something does break.

891
00:34:47.770 --> 00:34:49.770
In thinking about the harness, it's something like,

892
00:34:49.770 --> 00:34:50.770
like a seam,

893
00:34:50.770 --> 00:34:52.770
and the flight has been ended,

894
00:34:52.770 --> 00:34:55.810
that you can come down

895
00:34:55.810 --> 00:34:56.810
at an angle,

896
00:34:56.810 --> 00:34:57.810
because something's torn,

897
00:34:57.810 --> 00:34:59.770
then it's certainly out of the topic,

898
00:34:59.770 --> 00:35:05.200
go for the reserve.

899
00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:08.250
The basic principle

900
00:35:08.250 --> 00:35:09.250
of the second chance,

901
00:35:09.250 --> 00:35:11.250
when something's uncontrollable,

902
00:35:11.250 --> 00:35:13.250
that we don't see the second chance,

903
00:35:13.250 --> 00:35:14.250
the reserve,

904
00:35:14.250 --> 00:35:15.250
is really, really important

905
00:35:15.250 --> 00:35:17.250
for the whole flying journey.

906
00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:18.250
I say with that,

907
00:35:18.250 --> 00:35:19.250
where it's a second chance,

908
00:35:19.250 --> 00:35:21.250
when you have to hand

909
00:35:21.250 --> 00:35:23.250
and mouth know,

910
00:35:23.250 --> 00:35:24.250
how it works,

911
00:35:24.250 --> 00:35:26.250
the whole system.

912
00:35:26.250 --> 00:35:27.250
How it works,

913
00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:29.250
we absolutely have to ask through the flight school

914
00:35:29.250 --> 00:35:30.250
still,

915
00:35:30.250 --> 00:35:31.250
I'd like that,

916
00:35:31.250 --> 00:35:32.250
for the students in Zurich,

917
00:35:32.250 --> 00:35:33.250
that they know

918
00:35:33.250 --> 00:35:35.250
where the reserve handle is,

919
00:35:35.250 --> 00:35:37.250
a good habit, too,

920
00:35:37.250 --> 00:35:38.250
for example,

921
00:35:38.250 --> 00:35:40.250
if you do a normal flight check

922
00:35:40.250 --> 00:35:42.250
with the flat of your hand on every flight,

923
00:35:42.250 --> 00:35:43.250
where you touch,

924
00:35:43.250 --> 00:35:44.250
where the reserve is,

925
00:35:44.250 --> 00:35:46.250
so that in an emergency

926
00:35:46.250 --> 00:35:47.250
you also know,

927
00:35:47.250 --> 00:35:49.250
how to react.

928
00:35:49.250 --> 00:35:51.250
The reserve is a big topic.

929
00:35:51.250 --> 00:35:53.250
There are still things to discuss,

930
00:35:53.250 --> 00:35:55.250
like how often to repack it.

931
00:35:55.250 --> 00:35:57.250
Some manufacturers

932
00:35:57.250 --> 00:35:58.250
say,

933
00:35:58.250 --> 00:36:00.250
every 6 months a fresh repack.

934
00:36:00.250 --> 00:36:01.250
Practice shows,

935
00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:03.250
every 6 months to once a year.

936
00:36:03.250 --> 00:36:05.250
Anything beyond that you don't really want,

937
00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:07.250
packed longer than a year,

938
00:36:07.250 --> 00:36:09.250
rather it should be refolded.

939
00:36:09.250 --> 00:36:12.250
That's a big topic

940
00:36:12.250 --> 00:36:15.250
and a course in itself.

941
00:36:15.250 --> 00:36:18.250
What we've covered here

942
00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:20.250
in flight practice,

943
00:36:20.250 --> 00:36:22.600
is that

944
00:36:22.600 --> 00:36:24.600
which is asked at the brevet,

945
00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:25.600
I know,

946
00:36:25.600 --> 00:36:26.600
and I hope

947
00:36:26.600 --> 00:36:28.600
you enjoyed the talk.

948
00:36:28.600 --> 00:36:31.600
I thank you very much

949
00:36:31.600 --> 00:36:32.600
for your attention

950
00:36:32.600 --> 00:36:34.600
and see you soon.
